factors: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorders

items.text: I often feel tense and on edge, even when there's no apparent reason.
items.rationale: Persistent tension and unease are characteristic of anxiety disorders.

items.text: She frequently experiences sudden, intense bouts of fear that make her heart race.
items.rationale: Panic attacks are a hallmark of anxiety disorders.

items.text: I avoid social situations because I'm afraid of being judged.
items.rationale: Social anxiety involves fear of negative evaluation in social contexts.

items.text: He constantly worries about his health, despite reassurance from doctors.
items.rationale: Health anxiety is a common manifestation of anxiety disorders.

items.text: I have trouble sleeping because my mind won't stop racing.
items.rationale: Racing thoughts and insomnia are common in anxiety disorders.

items.text: She feels a sense of dread when thinking about the future.
items.rationale: Anticipatory anxiety about future events is typical in anxiety disorders.

items.text: I get extremely anxious in crowded places.
items.rationale: Agoraphobia and anxiety in crowded spaces are common in anxiety disorders.

items.text: He checks the locks multiple times before leaving the house.
items.rationale: Compulsive checking is a behavior associated with anxiety disorders.

items.text: I feel a constant need to be reassured by others.
items.rationale: Seeking reassurance is a common behavior in anxiety disorders.

items.text: She often feels a tightness in her chest when stressed.
items.rationale: Physical symptoms like chest tightness are common in anxiety disorders.

items.text: I get nervous about things that others seem to handle easily.
items.rationale: Excessive nervousness in everyday situations is typical of anxiety disorders.

items.text: He avoids driving because he's afraid of having a panic attack.
items.rationale: Avoidance of activities due to fear of panic is common in anxiety disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel anxious, but it usually passes quickly.
items.rationale: Transient anxiety can occur in anxiety disorders but is less characteristic.

items.text: She worries about her performance at work, but it motivates her to do better.
items.rationale: Performance anxiety can be adaptive, making it less clearly pathological.

items.text: I feel down and anxious when I'm under a lot of stress.
items.rationale: Could map to Depressive Disorders due to the presence of low mood.

items.text: I have periods where I feel extremely energetic and don't need much sleep.
items.rationale: Manic episodes involve increased energy and reduced need for sleep.

items.text: He experiences mood swings that last for days or weeks.
items.rationale: Prolonged mood swings are characteristic of bipolar disorder.

items.text: I sometimes feel on top of the world and then suddenly very low.
items.rationale: Rapid cycling between high and low moods is typical in bipolar disorder.

items.text: She has grand ideas and feels invincible during certain periods.
items.rationale: Grandiosity and feelings of invincibility are symptoms of mania.

items.text: I sometimes spend money recklessly when I'm feeling really good.
items.rationale: Impulsive spending is a common behavior during manic episodes.

items.text: He talks rapidly and jumps from topic to topic when he's in a good mood.
items.rationale: Pressured speech and flight of ideas are symptoms of mania.

items.text: I have periods where I feel extremely irritable and agitated.
items.rationale: Irritability and agitation can occur during manic or hypomanic episodes.

items.text: She sometimes feels so euphoric that she can't sit still.
items.rationale: Euphoria and increased activity are signs of mania.

items.text: I have trouble concentrating when I'm in a high-energy state.
items.rationale: Difficulty concentrating is common during manic episodes.

items.text: He sometimes feels like he can accomplish anything, no matter how unrealistic.
items.rationale: Unrealistic optimism and overconfidence are symptoms of mania.

items.text: I have periods where I feel very creative and productive.
items.rationale: Increased creativity and productivity can occur during hypomanic episodes.

items.text: She sometimes feels very energetic but not necessarily happy.
items.rationale: Increased energy without euphoria can still indicate hypomania.

items.text: I feel restless and can't sit still when I'm excited.
items.rationale: Restlessness can occur in mania but is not exclusive to it.

items.text: I feel very low and have no energy for days at a time.
items.rationale: Could map to Depressive Disorders due to the presence of low energy and mood.

items.text: I often feel sad and hopeless, even when things are going well.
items.rationale: Persistent sadness and hopelessness are core symptoms of depression.

items.text: He has lost interest in activities he used to enjoy.
items.rationale: Anhedonia, or loss of interest, is a key symptom of depression.

items.text: I have trouble getting out of bed in the morning due to lack of motivation.
items.rationale: Lack of motivation and energy are common in depressive disorders.

items.text: She feels worthless and guilty most of the time.
items.rationale: Feelings of worthlessness and guilt are common in depression.

items.text: I have difficulty concentrating and making decisions.
items.rationale: Cognitive difficulties are a symptom of depressive disorders.

items.text: He has noticed a significant change in his appetite and weight.
items.rationale: Changes in appetite and weight are common in depression.

items.text: I feel tired all the time, no matter how much I sleep.
items.rationale: Chronic fatigue is a common symptom of depressive disorders.

items.text: She often thinks about death or dying.
items.rationale: Recurrent thoughts of death are a serious symptom of depression.

items.text: I feel like I'm moving in slow motion.
items.rationale: Psychomotor retardation is a symptom of depressive disorders.

items.text: He has trouble sleeping, often waking up in the early hours.
items.rationale: Insomnia, especially early morning awakening, is common in depression.

items.text: I feel like I'm a burden to others.
items.rationale: Feelings of being a burden are common in depressive disorders.

items.text: She sometimes feels down but can still enjoy some activities.
items.rationale: Mild depressive symptoms can allow for some enjoyment, making it less clear.

items.text: I feel sad when I'm alone, but it gets better when I'm with friends.
items.rationale: Situational improvement in mood can occur in mild depression.

items.text: I get angry and irritable when I'm feeling down.
items.rationale: Could map to Disruptive, Impulse-Control, and Conduct Disorders due to irritability.

items.text: He often acts without thinking about the consequences.
items.rationale: Impulsivity is a key feature of these disorders.

items.text: I have a hard time controlling my temper.
items.rationale: Difficulty with anger management is common in these disorders.

items.text: She often argues with authority figures.
items.rationale: Oppositional behavior is characteristic of these disorders.

items.text: I sometimes destroy things when I'm upset.
items.rationale: Destructive behavior is a symptom of these disorders.

items.text: He often blames others for his mistakes.
items.rationale: Externalizing blame is common in these disorders.

items.text: I have been in trouble with the law for aggressive behavior.
items.rationale: Legal issues due to aggression are common in these disorders.

items.text: She often lies to get what she wants.
items.rationale: Deceptive behavior is a symptom of these disorders.

items.text: I have a hard time following rules.
items.rationale: Rule-breaking behavior is characteristic of these disorders.

items.text: He often feels restless and can't sit still.
items.rationale: Restlessness and hyperactivity are common in these disorders.

items.text: I sometimes take things that don't belong to me.
items.rationale: Stealing is a behavior associated with these disorders.

items.text: She often feels the need to provoke others.
items.rationale: Provocative behavior is a symptom of these disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I can't control my impulses.
items.rationale: General impulsivity can be less specific to these disorders.

items.text: He gets into fights but usually regrets it afterward.
items.rationale: Regret after aggression can indicate less severe pathology.

items.text: I feel detached from my surroundings, like I'm in a dream.
items.rationale: Derealization is a key symptom of dissociative disorders.

items.text: She sometimes feels like she's watching herself from outside her body.
items.rationale: Depersonalization is a symptom of dissociative disorders.

items.text: I have gaps in my memory for important personal events.
items.rationale: Amnesia for personal events is characteristic of dissociative disorders.

items.text: He sometimes feels like different parts of him are in conflict.
items.rationale: Internal conflict and identity disturbance are symptoms of dissociative disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I'm not real.
items.rationale: Feelings of unreality are common in dissociative disorders.

items.text: She has trouble remembering who she is during stressful times.
items.rationale: Identity confusion during stress is a symptom of dissociative disorders.

items.text: I feel like I'm in a fog and can't think clearly.
items.rationale: Cognitive fog is a symptom of dissociative disorders.

items.text: He sometimes feels like he's two different people.
items.rationale: Identity alteration is a symptom of dissociative disorders.

items.text: I have trouble recognizing familiar places.
items.rationale: Derealization can involve difficulty recognizing familiar environments.

items.text: She feels like time is moving differently for her.
items.rationale: Altered perception of time is a symptom of dissociative disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I'm a stranger to myself.
items.rationale: Self-estrangement is a symptom of dissociative disorders.

items.text: He sometimes feels disconnected from his emotions.
items.rationale: Emotional detachment can occur in dissociative disorders but is less specific.

items.text: I feel like I'm living in a movie sometimes.
items.rationale: This can indicate derealization but is less clearly pathological.

items.text: I feel like I'm not myself when I'm under a lot of stress.
items.rationale: Could map to Anxiety Disorders due to stress-related symptoms.

items.text: He often wets the bed at night.
items.rationale: Nocturnal enuresis is a primary symptom of elimination disorders.

items.text: I have accidents during the day, even though I'm old enough to use the toilet.
items.rationale: Daytime incontinence is a symptom of elimination disorders.

items.text: She sometimes soils her clothes without realizing it.
items.rationale: Encopresis, or soiling, is a symptom of elimination disorders.

items.text: I have to wear protection because I can't always control my bladder.
items.rationale: Incontinence requiring protection is a symptom of elimination disorders.

items.text: He has trouble staying dry through the night.
items.rationale: Nocturnal enuresis is a common symptom of elimination disorders.

items.text: I sometimes have accidents when I'm stressed.
items.rationale: Stress-related incontinence can occur in elimination disorders.

items.text: She avoids sleepovers because she's afraid of wetting the bed.
items.rationale: Fear of nocturnal enuresis can lead to avoidance behaviors.

items.text: I have to go to the bathroom frequently to avoid accidents.
items.rationale: Frequent urination to prevent accidents is a symptom of elimination disorders.

items.text: He sometimes has bowel movements in inappropriate places.
items.rationale: Inappropriate bowel movements are a symptom of elimination disorders.

items.text: I feel embarrassed about my accidents.
items.rationale: Embarrassment about incontinence is common in elimination disorders.

items.text: She has been toilet trained but still has accidents.
items.rationale: Continued accidents post-toilet training are a symptom of elimination disorders.

items.text: I sometimes have accidents when I'm really focused on something else.
items.rationale: Accidents due to distraction can occur but are less specific.

items.text: He has accidents but only when he's very tired.
items.rationale: Fatigue-related incontinence can occur but is less clearly pathological.

items.text: I have accidents when I'm anxious.
items.rationale: Could map to Anxiety Disorders due to stress-related symptoms.

items.text: I often feel like I'm too fat, even though others say I'm thin.
items.rationale: Distorted body image is a key symptom of eating disorders.

items.text: She restricts her food intake to lose weight.
items.rationale: Food restriction is a common behavior in eating disorders.

items.text: I sometimes eat large amounts of food in a short period.
items.rationale: Binge eating is a symptom of eating disorders.

items.text: He often feels guilty after eating.
items.rationale: Guilt after eating is common in eating disorders.

items.text: I use laxatives to control my weight.
items.rationale: Laxative use for weight control is a behavior in eating disorders.

items.text: She exercises excessively to burn off calories.
items.rationale: Excessive exercise is a compensatory behavior in eating disorders.

items.text: I feel out of control when I start eating.
items.rationale: Loss of control over eating is a symptom of eating disorders.

items.text: He avoids eating in front of others.
items.rationale: Avoidance of eating in social settings is common in eating disorders.

items.text: I have a fear of gaining weight.
items.rationale: Fear of weight gain is a core symptom of eating disorders.

items.text: She often skips meals to lose weight.
items.rationale: Skipping meals is a common behavior in eating disorders.

items.text: I sometimes make myself vomit after eating.
items.rationale: Self-induced vomiting is a compensatory behavior in eating disorders.

items.text: He feels anxious about eating certain foods.
items.rationale: Food-related anxiety can occur but is less specific to eating disorders.

items.text: I sometimes eat when I'm not hungry.
items.rationale: Eating without hunger can occur in eating disorders but is less specific.

items.text: I feel anxious about my body image.
items.rationale: Could map to Anxiety Disorders due to body image-related anxiety.

items.text: I feel like I'm in the wrong body.
items.rationale: A strong sense of incongruence between experienced and assigned gender is key.

items.text: She often wishes she had been born a different gender.
items.rationale: Desire to be another gender is a core symptom of gender dysphoria.

items.text: I feel distressed when people refer to me by my birth gender.
items.rationale: Distress related to gendered interactions is common in gender dysphoria.

items.text: He prefers clothing typically associated with another gender.
items.rationale: Preference for gender-nonconforming clothing is a symptom of gender dysphoria.

items.text: I feel uncomfortable with my body because it doesn't match my gender identity.
items.rationale: Body discomfort due to gender incongruence is a symptom of gender dysphoria.

items.text: She often imagines herself as a different gender.
items.rationale: Imagining oneself as another gender is common in gender dysphoria.

items.text: I feel a strong desire to change my physical appearance to match my gender identity.
items.rationale: Desire for physical transition is a symptom of gender dysphoria.

items.text: He feels more comfortable when people use his chosen name and pronouns.
items.rationale: Comfort with affirmed gender identity is common in gender dysphoria.

items.text: I feel anxious about puberty because it will change my body in ways I don't want.
items.rationale: Anxiety about puberty-related changes is common in gender dysphoria.

items.text: She often feels like she has to hide her true gender identity.
items.rationale: Hiding one's gender identity is a common experience in gender dysphoria.

items.text: I feel disconnected from my gender assigned at birth.
items.rationale: Disconnection from assigned gender is a symptom of gender dysphoria.

items.text: He sometimes feels like he doesn't fit in with either gender.
items.rationale: Feeling between genders can occur in gender dysphoria but is less specific.

items.text: I feel uncomfortable with gendered expectations.
items.rationale: Discomfort with gender roles can occur but is less specific to gender dysphoria.

items.text: I feel anxious about how others perceive my gender.
items.rationale: Could map to Anxiety Disorders due to social anxiety aspects.

items.text: I sometimes have uncontrollable movements after taking medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Involuntary movements are a symptom of medication-induced movement disorders.

items.text: He experiences muscle stiffness after starting a new medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Muscle stiffness is a common side effect of certain medications.

items.text: I have noticed tremors in my hands since taking this drug.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Tremors are a common side effect of medication-induced movement disorders.

items.text: She feels dizzy and lightheaded after taking her medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Dizziness is a common adverse effect of medications.

items.text: I have difficulty sitting still due to restlessness from my medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Restlessness is a symptom of medication-induced movement disorders.

items.text: He experiences involuntary facial movements after starting a new drug.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Involuntary facial movements are a symptom of medication-induced movement disorders.

items.text: I feel nauseous and have an upset stomach after taking my medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Nausea is a common adverse effect of medications.

items.text: She has trouble sleeping due to side effects from her medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Insomnia is a common adverse effect of medications.

items.text: I have noticed a change in my appetite since starting this medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Appetite changes are common adverse effects of medications.

items.text: He experiences blurred vision after taking his medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Blurred vision is a common adverse effect of medications.

items.text: I feel unusually tired after taking my medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Fatigue is a common adverse effect of medications.

items.text: She sometimes feels anxious after taking her medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Anxiety can be a side effect of medications but is less specific.

items.text: I have noticed mood swings since starting this medication.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Mood swings can be a side effect of medications but are less specific.

items.text: I feel restless and can't sit still, but it might be due to stress.
items.expected_factor: Medication-Induced Movement Disorders and Other Adverse Effects of Medication
items.rationale: Could map to Anxiety Disorders due to stress-related restlessness.

items.text: I often forget things that just happened.
items.rationale: Short-term memory loss is a key symptom of neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: He has trouble finding the right words when speaking.
items.rationale: Language difficulties are common in neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: I get lost in familiar places.
items.rationale: Spatial disorientation is a symptom of neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: She has difficulty following conversations.
items.rationale: Difficulty with conversation is common in neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: I have trouble remembering names of people I know well.
items.rationale: Difficulty recalling familiar names is a symptom of neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: He often misplaces items and can't find them later.
items.rationale: Frequent misplacement of items is common in neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: I have trouble planning and organizing tasks.
items.rationale: Executive function deficits are a symptom of neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: She often repeats herself in conversations.
items.rationale: Repetitive speech is common in neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: I feel confused about the time or date.
items.rationale: Temporal disorientation is a symptom of neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: He has difficulty recognizing familiar faces.
items.rationale: Prosopagnosia, or face blindness, is a symptom of neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: I have trouble with complex tasks that I used to do easily.
items.rationale: Difficulty with complex tasks is common in neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: She sometimes feels disoriented in new environments.
items.rationale: Disorientation in new settings can occur but is less specific.

items.text: I have trouble concentrating when I'm tired.
items.rationale: Concentration difficulties can occur but are less specific to neurocognitive disorders.

items.text: I feel anxious when I can't remember things.
items.rationale: Could map to Anxiety Disorders due to anxiety about memory loss.

items.text: I have difficulty understanding social cues and often miss nonverbal signals.
items.rationale: Difficulty with social cues is a common feature of neurodevelopmental disorders like autism spectrum disorder.

items.text: I struggle to stay focused on tasks and am easily distracted.
items.rationale: Inattention and distractibility are key symptoms of ADHD, a neurodevelopmental disorder.

items.text: I often repeat certain actions or phrases without realizing it.
items.rationale: Repetitive behaviors are characteristic of neurodevelopmental disorders such as autism.

items.text: I find it hard to make eye contact during conversations.
items.rationale: Avoidance of eye contact is a common trait in individuals with autism spectrum disorder.

items.text: I have a hard time organizing my daily activities.
items.rationale: Organizational difficulties are often seen in ADHD.

items.text: I tend to hyperfocus on topics that interest me.
items.rationale: Hyperfocus is a symptom associated with ADHD.

items.text: I have trouble understanding jokes or sarcasm.
items.rationale: Difficulty with abstract language is common in autism spectrum disorder.

items.text: I often feel overwhelmed by sensory input like loud noises or bright lights.
items.rationale: Sensory sensitivities are frequently reported in autism spectrum disorder.

items.text: I have a strong need for routine and get upset when it changes.
items.rationale: A need for routine is a common feature of autism spectrum disorder.

items.text: I find it difficult to follow multi-step instructions.
items.rationale: Difficulty with complex instructions is often seen in ADHD.

items.text: I have a hard time sitting still for long periods.
items.rationale: Hyperactivity is a core symptom of ADHD.

items.text: I often interrupt others during conversations.
items.rationale: Impulsivity, such as interrupting, is a symptom of ADHD.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I don't fit in socially.
items.rationale: Social difficulties can be a feature of neurodevelopmental disorders but also other conditions.

items.text: I have a very narrow range of interests.
items.rationale: Narrow interests are common in autism but can also be seen in other conditions.

items.text: I often feel anxious in social situations.
items.rationale: Social anxiety can be related to neurodevelopmental disorders or anxiety disorders.

items.text: I feel compelled to check things multiple times to make sure they're done right.
items.rationale: Compulsive checking is a hallmark of obsessive-compulsive disorder.

items.text: I have intrusive thoughts that I can't seem to control.
items.rationale: Intrusive thoughts are a core feature of obsessive-compulsive disorder.

items.text: I spend a lot of time organizing things to make them 'just right.'
items.rationale: Excessive organizing is a common compulsion in OCD.

items.text: I feel the need to wash my hands repeatedly throughout the day.
items.rationale: Compulsive hand washing is a typical behavior in OCD.

items.text: I often feel driven to count things around me.
items.rationale: Compulsive counting is a symptom of OCD.

items.text: I have rituals that I must perform to prevent bad things from happening.
items.rationale: Ritualistic behaviors to prevent harm are common in OCD.

items.text: I feel anxious if things are not in their proper place.
items.rationale: Anxiety about orderliness is a feature of OCD.

items.text: I have a strong urge to hoard items, even if they're not useful.
items.rationale: Hoarding is a related disorder within the OCD spectrum.

items.text: I feel the need to repeat certain phrases to myself.
items.rationale: Repetitive phrases can be a compulsion in OCD.

items.text: I often worry excessively about contamination.
items.rationale: Fear of contamination is a common obsession in OCD.

items.text: I feel compelled to arrange things symmetrically.
items.rationale: Symmetry compulsion is a symptom of OCD.

items.text: I sometimes feel like my thoughts are not my own.
items.rationale: This can be related to OCD but also to dissociative disorders.

items.text: I often feel the need to confess my thoughts to others.
items.rationale: Confession can be a compulsion in OCD but also seen in anxiety disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I have to do things in a specific order to avoid anxiety.
items.rationale: Could relate to OCD or anxiety disorders due to ritualistic behavior.

items.text: I often feel overwhelmed by the demands of daily life.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Feeling overwhelmed can be a focus of clinical attention without a specific disorder.

items.text: I have difficulty managing my stress levels.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Stress management issues can be a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I often feel like I'm not living up to my potential.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Concerns about potential can be a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I struggle with maintaining healthy relationships.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Relationship issues are often a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I have a hard time balancing work and personal life.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Work-life balance issues can be a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I often feel like I'm not in control of my life.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Feeling out of control can be a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I have difficulty setting and achieving goals.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Goal-setting issues can be a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I often feel disconnected from my emotions.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Emotional disconnection can be a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I struggle with self-esteem and self-worth.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Self-esteem issues are often a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I have a hard time coping with change.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Coping with change can be a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I often feel like I'm not good enough.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Feelings of inadequacy can be a focus of clinical attention.

items.text: I have difficulty expressing my needs to others.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Communication issues can be a focus of clinical attention but also relate to social anxiety.

items.text: I often feel like I'm not heard or understood.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Feeling misunderstood can be a focus of clinical attention but also relate to personality disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I'm just going through the motions in life.
items.expected_factor: Other Conditions That May Be a Focus of Clinical Attention
items.rationale: Could relate to existential issues or depressive disorders.

items.text: I have sexual fantasies that others might find unusual.
items.rationale: Unusual sexual fantasies can be indicative of paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I feel aroused by things that are not typically considered sexual.
items.rationale: Arousal by atypical stimuli is a feature of paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I have urges to engage in sexual activities that others might find inappropriate.
items.rationale: Inappropriate sexual urges are characteristic of paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I often feel the need to act on my sexual fantasies.
items.rationale: Acting on atypical sexual fantasies is a feature of paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I have a strong preference for specific objects or situations for sexual arousal.
items.rationale: Specific preferences for arousal are indicative of paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I feel distressed by my sexual interests.
items.rationale: Distress about sexual interests is a criterion for paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I have been told that my sexual behavior is unusual.
items.rationale: Unusual sexual behavior can indicate a paraphilic disorder.

items.text: I have sexual interests that could cause harm to others.
items.rationale: Harmful sexual interests are a concern in paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I feel compelled to engage in sexual activities that are not socially acceptable.
items.rationale: Compulsion to engage in socially unacceptable activities is a feature of paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I have sexual fantasies that involve non-consenting partners.
items.rationale: Non-consensual fantasies are a serious concern in paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I often feel ashamed of my sexual desires.
items.rationale: Shame about sexual desires can be related to paraphilic disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel like my sexual interests are out of my control.
items.rationale: Feeling out of control can relate to paraphilic disorders but also impulse control disorders.

items.text: I have been criticized for my sexual preferences.
items.rationale: Criticism of sexual preferences can relate to paraphilic disorders but also cultural differences.

items.text: I sometimes feel like my sexual interests are a part of my identity.
items.rationale: Could relate to paraphilic disorders or identity issues.

items.text: I often feel like I don't know who I really am.
items.rationale: Identity disturbance is a common feature of personality disorders.

items.text: I have intense and unstable relationships.
items.rationale: Unstable relationships are characteristic of borderline personality disorder.

items.text: I often act impulsively without thinking about the consequences.
items.rationale: Impulsivity is a key feature of several personality disorders.

items.text: I have a strong fear of abandonment.
items.rationale: Fear of abandonment is a hallmark of borderline personality disorder.

items.text: I often feel empty inside.
items.rationale: Chronic feelings of emptiness are common in borderline personality disorder.

items.text: I have difficulty trusting others.
items.rationale: Distrust is a feature of paranoid personality disorder.

items.text: I often feel like I'm better than others.
items.rationale: Grandiosity is a feature of narcissistic personality disorder.

items.text: I have a hard time controlling my anger.

items.text: I have difficulty achieving or maintaining an erection.

items.text: I have trouble falling asleep at night.
items.rationale: Difficulty falling asleep is a symptom of insomnia, a sleep-wake disorder.

items.text: I often wake up in the middle of the night and can't get back to sleep.
items.rationale: Middle-of-the-night awakenings are common in sleep-wake disorders.

items.text: I feel excessively sleepy during the day.
items.rationale: Excessive daytime sleepiness is a symptom of sleep-wake disorders.

items.text: I have trouble staying awake during the day.
items.rationale: Daytime sleepiness is a key feature of sleep-wake disorders.

items.text: I often have nightmares that disrupt my sleep.
items.rationale: Nightmares are a symptom of parasomnias, a type of sleep-wake disorder.

items.text: I have difficulty maintaining a regular sleep schedule.
items.rationale: Irregular sleep schedules are common in circadian rhythm sleep-wake disorders.

items.text: I often feel like I haven't slept well, even after a full night's sleep.
items.rationale: Non-restorative sleep is a symptom of sleep-wake disorders.

items.text: I have been told that I snore loudly.
items.rationale: Loud snoring is a symptom of sleep apnea, a sleep-wake disorder.

items.text: I often feel like I can't move when I wake up or fall asleep.
items.rationale: Sleep paralysis is a symptom of sleep-wake disorders.

items.text: I have been told that I stop breathing during sleep.
items.rationale: Apneas are a symptom of sleep apnea, a sleep-wake disorder.

items.text: I often feel like I need to nap during the day.
items.rationale: Daytime napping can indicate a sleep-wake disorder.

items.text: I sometimes feel like my sleep problems are affecting my mood.
items.rationale: Mood impact can relate to sleep-wake disorders but also mood disorders.

items.text: I often feel like my sleep issues are related to stress.
items.rationale: Stress can exacerbate sleep-wake disorders but also relate to stress disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel like my sleep problems are due to anxiety.
items.rationale: Could relate to sleep-wake disorders or anxiety disorders.

items.text: I often feel like I have multiple physical symptoms that can't be explained.
items.rationale: Unexplained physical symptoms are a hallmark of somatic symptom disorders.

items.text: I frequently worry about my health.
items.rationale: Excessive health worry is a key feature of somatic symptom disorders.

items.text: I often feel like my symptoms are more severe than others think.
items.rationale: Perception of severe symptoms is common in somatic symptom disorders.

items.text: I have been to many doctors but still don't have a diagnosis.
items.rationale: Frequent doctor visits without diagnosis are typical in somatic symptom disorders.

items.text: I often feel like my symptoms are not taken seriously.
items.rationale: Feeling dismissed is common in somatic symptom disorders.

items.text: I have physical symptoms that cause significant distress.
items.rationale: Distress from physical symptoms is a feature of somatic symptom disorders.

items.text: I often feel like my body is not functioning properly.
items.rationale: Perceived dysfunction is common in somatic symptom disorders.

items.text: I have symptoms that interfere with my daily life.

items.text: I often feel like my symptoms are a sign of a serious illness.

items.text: I have been told that my symptoms are 'all in my head.'
items.rationale: Psychosomatic perceptions are common in somatic symptom disorders.

items.text: I often feel like my symptoms are not improving despite treatment.

items.text: I sometimes feel like my symptoms are related to stress.
items.rationale: Stress-related symptoms can relate to somatic symptom disorders but also stress disorders.

items.text: I often feel like my symptoms are misunderstood by others.
items.rationale: Misunderstanding can relate to somatic symptom disorders but also communication issues.

items.text: I sometimes feel like my symptoms are a way to cope with emotional pain.
items.rationale: Could relate to somatic symptom disorders or emotional disorders.

items.text: I often feel like I need a drink to relax.

items.text: I have tried to cut down on my drinking but haven't been able to.
items.rationale: Inability to cut down is a criterion for substance use disorders.

items.text: I often use substances to cope with stress.
items.rationale: Using substances to cope is a feature of substance use disorders.

items.text: I have experienced withdrawal symptoms when not using a substance.
items.rationale: Withdrawal symptoms are a key feature of substance use disorders.

items.text: I often feel like I need more of a substance to get the same effect.
items.rationale: Tolerance is a symptom of substance use disorders.

items.text: I have neglected responsibilities because of substance use.
items.rationale: Neglecting responsibilities is a criterion for substance use disorders.

items.text: I often feel guilty about my substance use.
items.rationale: Guilt about use is common in substance use disorders.

items.text: I have continued to use substances despite negative consequences.
items.rationale: Continued use despite harm is a feature of substance use disorders.

items.text: I often feel like I can't control my substance use.

items.text: I have used substances in dangerous situations.

items.text: I often feel like I need a substance to feel normal.

items.text: I sometimes feel like my substance use is affecting my relationships.
items.rationale: Relationship impact can relate to substance use disorders but also relationship issues.

items.text: I often feel like my substance use is out of my control.

items.text: I often have nightmares about past traumatic events.

items.text: I have trouble remembering important parts of a traumatic event.

items.text: I feel detached from people around me.

items.rationale: Intrusive thoughts and concentration issues are symptoms of trauma-related disorders.

items.text: I feel a sense of hopelessness about the future.
items.rationale: Hopelessness can be a symptom of trauma-related disorders.

items.text: I have physical reactions, like sweating or a racing heart, when reminded of a traumatic event.
items.rationale: Physical reactions to reminders are symptoms of trauma-related disorders.

items.text: I feel emotionally numb and unable to experience positive emotions.
items.rationale: Emotional numbing is a symptom of trauma-related disorders.

items.text: I have difficulty sleeping because of anxiety related to past trauma.
items.rationale: Sleep disturbances due to anxiety are common in trauma-related disorders.

items.text: I feel irritable and have angry outbursts without much provocation.
items.rationale: Irritability and anger are symptoms of trauma-related disorders.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I'm reliving a traumatic event.
